"New ``device`` keyword argument to all array creation functions "
"(``asarray``, ``arange``, ``empty``, ``empty_like``, ``eye``, ``full``, "
"``full_like``, ``linspace``, ``ones``, ``ones_like``, ``zeros``, and "
"``zeros_like``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:596
msgid "``device`` would effectively do nothing, since NumPy is CPU only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:599
msgid "Elementwise Functions Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:607
msgid "Various functions have been renamed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:609 ../../../reference/array_api.rst:713
#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:740
msgid "See :ref:`array_api-name-changes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:610
msgid ""
"Elementwise functions are only defined for given input type combinations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:613
msgid "See :ref:`array_api-type-strictness`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:614
msgid ""
"``bitwise_left_shift`` and ``bitwise_right_shift`` are only defined for "
"``x2`` nonnegative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:618
msgid ""
"``ceil``, ``floor``, and ``trunc`` return an integer with integer input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:621
msgid ""
"``np.ceil``, ``np.floor``, and ``np.trunc`` return a floating-point dtype on "
"integer dtype input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:627
msgid "Linear Algebra Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:635
msgid "``cholesky`` includes an ``upper`` keyword argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:638
msgid "``cross`` does not allow size 2 vectors (only size 3)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:641
msgid "``diagonal`` operates on the last two axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:643
msgid ""
"Strictly speaking this can be **compatible** because ``diagonal`` is moved "
"to the ``linalg`` namespace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:645
msgid "``eigh``, ``qr``, ``slogdet`` and ``svd`` return a named tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:647
msgid ""
"The corresponding ``numpy`` functions return a ``tuple``, with the resulting "
"arrays in the same order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:649
msgid "New functions ``matrix_norm`` and ``vector_norm``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:651
msgid ""
"The ``norm`` function has been omitted from the array API and split into "
"``matrix_norm`` for matrix norms and ``vector_norm`` for vector norms. Note "
"that ``vector_norm`` supports any number of axes, whereas ``np.linalg.norm`` "
"only supports a single axis for vector norms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:655
msgid "``matrix_rank`` has an ``rtol`` keyword argument instead of ``tol``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:657
msgid ""
"In the array API, ``rtol`` filters singular values smaller than ``rtol * "
"largest_singular_value``. In ``np.linalg.matrix_rank``, ``tol`` filters "
"singular values smaller than ``tol``. Furthermore, the default value for "
"``rtol`` is ``max(M, N) * eps``, whereas the default value of ``tol`` in "
"``np.linalg.matrix_rank`` is ``S.max() * max(M, N) * eps``, where ``S`` is "
"the singular values of the input. The new flag name is compatible but the "
"default change is breaking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:664
msgid "``matrix_rank`` does not support 1-dimensional arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:667
msgid "New function ``matrix_transpose``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:669
msgid ""
"Unlike ``np.transpose``, ``matrix_transpose`` only transposes the last two "
"axes. See `the spec definition <https://data-apis.org/array-api/latest/"
"API_specification/generated/signatures.linear_algebra_functions."
"matrix_transpose.html#signatures.linear_algebra_functions."
"matrix_transpose>`__"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:672
msgid "``outer`` only supports 1-dimensional arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:674
msgid ""
"The spec currently only specifies behavior on 1-D arrays but future behavior "
"will likely be to broadcast, rather than flatten, which is what ``np.outer`` "
"does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:677
msgid "``pinv`` has an ``rtol`` keyword argument instead of ``rcond``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:679
msgid ""
"The meaning of ``rtol`` and ``rcond`` is the same, but the default value for "
"``rtol`` is ``max(M, N) * eps``, whereas the default value for ``rcond`` is "
"``1e-15``. The new flag name is compatible but the default change is "
"breaking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:683
msgid ""
"``solve`` only accepts ``x2`` as a vector when it is exactly 1-dimensional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:686
msgid ""
"The ``np.linalg.solve`` behavior is ambiguous. See `this numpy issue "
"<https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/15349>`__ and `this array API "
"specification issue <https://github.com/data-apis/array-api/issues/285>`__ "
"for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:691
msgid "New function ``svdvals``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:693
msgid "Equivalent to ``np.linalg.svd(compute_uv=False)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:694
msgid "The ``axis`` keyword to ``tensordot`` must be a tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:696
msgid "In ``np.tensordot``, it can also be an array or array-like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:697
msgid "``trace`` operates on the last two axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:699
msgid ""
"``np.trace`` operates on the first two axes by default. Note that the array "
"API ``trace`` does not allow specifying which axes to operate on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:703
msgid "Manipulation Functions Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:711
msgid "Various functions have been renamed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:714
msgid "``concat`` has different default casting rules from ``np.concatenate``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:716
msgid ""
"No cross-kind casting. No value-based casting on scalars (when axis=None)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:717
msgid "``stack`` has different default casting rules from ``np.stack``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:720
msgid "New function ``permute_dims``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:722
msgid ""
"Unlike ``np.transpose``, the ``axis`` keyword argument to ``permute_dims`` "
"is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:724
msgid "``reshape`` function has a ``copy`` keyword argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:726
msgid "See https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/9818."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:729 ../../../reference/array_api.rst:752
msgid "Set Functions Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:737
msgid ""
"New functions ``unique_all``, ``unique_counts``, ``unique_inverse``, and "
"``unique_values``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:741
msgid "The four ``unique_*`` functions return a named tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:744
msgid ""
"``unique_all`` and ``unique_indices`` return indices with the same shape as "
"``x``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:747
msgid "See https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/20638."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:760
msgid ""
"``argsort`` and ``sort`` have a ``stable`` keyword argument instead of "
"``kind``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:763
msgid ""
"``stable`` is a boolean keyword argument, defaulting to ``True``. ``kind`` "
"takes a string, defaulting to ``\"quicksort\"``. ``stable=True`` is "
"equivalent to ``kind=\"stable\"`` and ``kind=False`` is equivalent to "
"``kind=\"quicksort\"``, although any sorting algorithm is allowed by the "
"spec when ``stable=False``. The new flag name is compatible but the default "
"change is breaking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:769
msgid "``argsort`` and ``sort`` have a ``descending`` keyword argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:774
msgid "Statistical Functions Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:786
msgid ""
"The ``std`` and ``var`` functions have a ``correction`` keyword argument "
"instead of ``ddof``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:792
msgid "Other Differences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:800
msgid "Dtypes can only be spelled as dtype objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:802
msgid ""
"For example, ``numpy.array_api.asarray([0], dtype='int32')`` is not allowed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:804
msgid "``asarray`` is not implicitly called in any function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:806
msgid ""
"The exception is Python operators, which accept Python scalars in certain "
"cases (see :ref:`array_api-type-promotion-differences`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:808
msgid "``tril`` and ``triu`` require the input to be at least 2-D."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:811
msgid "finfo() return type uses ``float`` for the various attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:813
msgid ""
"The spec allows duck typing, so ``finfo`` returning dtype scalars is "
"considered type compatible with ``float``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:815
msgid "Positional arguments in every function are positional-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/array_api.rst:817
msgid ""
"See the spec for the exact signature of each function. Note that NumPy "
"ufuncs already use positional-only arguments, but non-ufuncs like "
"``asarray`` generally do not."
msgstr ""
